The Project¶

  1. This is a project with minimal scaffolding. Expect to use the the discussion forums to gain insights! It’s not cheating to ask others for opinions or perspectives!
  2. Be inquisitive, try out new things.
  3. Use the previous modules for insights into how to complete the functions! You'll have to combine Pillow, OpenCV, and Pytesseract
  4. There are hints provided in Coursera, feel free to explore the hints if needed. Each hint provide progressively more details on how to solve the issue. This project is intended to be comprehensive and difficult if you do it without the hints.

The Assignment¶

Take a ZIP file) of images and process them, using a library built into python that you need to learn how to use. A ZIP file takes several different files and compresses them, thus saving space, into one single file. The files in the ZIP file we provide are newspaper images (like you saw in week 3). Your task is to write python code which allows one to search through the images looking for the occurrences of keywords and faces. E.g. if you search for "pizza" it will return a contact sheet of all of the faces which were located on the newspaper page which mentions "pizza". This will test your ability to learn a new (library), your ability to use OpenCV to detect faces, your ability to use tesseract to do optical character recognition, and your ability to use PIL to composite images together into contact sheets.

Each page of the newspapers is saved as a single PNG image in a file called images.zip. These newspapers are in english, and contain a variety of stories, advertisements and images. Note: This file is fairly large (~200 MB) and may take some time to work with, I would encourage you to use small_img.zip for testing.

Here's an example of the output expected. Using the small_img.zip file, if I search for the string "Christopher" I should see the following image: If I were to use the images.zip file and search for "Mark" I should see the following image (note that there are times when there are no faces on a page, but a word is found!):

Note: That big file can take some time to process - for me it took nearly ten minutes! Use the small one for testing.

import zipfile
from zipfile import ZipFile
from zipfile import ZipInfo
from PIL import Image, ImageDraw
import pytesseract
import cv2 as cv
import numpy as np
import math

# loading the face detection classifier
face_cascade = cv.CascadeClassifier('readonly/haarcascade_frontalface_default.xml')

images_path = []
images = []
members_list = []
# Creating a Zip File Object
with ZipFile("./readonly/images.zip") as zip_file:
    # namelist return list of ZipFile members
    members_list = zip_file.infolist()
    for item in members_list:
        # extract the members and return str to their path 
        images_path.append(zip_file.extract(item))
    for item in images_path:
        images.append(Image.open(item))


# print(zip_file.namelist())
# the rest is up to you!

def research(images, keyword):
    results = {}
    faces = []
    count = 0
    for img in images:
        text = pytesseract.image_to_string(img)
        if keyword in text:
            image_to = cv.imread(images_path[count])
            gray = cv.cvtColor(image_to, cv.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
            faces.append(face_cascade.detectMultiScale(gray, scaleFactor=1.3, minNeighbors=5, minSize = (30, 30)))
            results[members_list[count]] = {}
            results[members_list[count]]["Image"] = []
            results[members_list[count]]["Bounding_Boxes"] = []
            for l_face in faces:
                for face in l_face:
                    box = [face[0], face[1], face[2] + face[0], face[3] + face[1]]
                    results[members_list[count]]["Bounding_Boxes"].append(box)
                    cropped_face = img.crop(box)
                    results[members_list[count]]["Image"].append(cropped_face)
                    
            pass
        count = count + 1
    # Now for second part which is creating Thumbnails :
        
    for img_name in results.keys():
        for face in results[img_name]['Image']:
            face.thumbnail((100,100),Image.ANTIALIAS)
    
    # =========== Now for the last part which consist of creating contact_sheet
    
    for img_name in members_list:
        if img_name in results.keys():
            print("Result found in file {}".format(img_name))
            cs_height = math.ceil(len(results[img_name]['Image'])/5)
            contact_sheet=Image.new('RGB',(500, 100*cs_height))
            width = 0
            height = 0
            for img in results[img_name]['Image']:
                contact_sheet.paste(img, (width, height))
                if width + 100 == contact_sheet.width:
                        width = 0
                        height += 100
                else:
                    width += 100
            display(contact_sheet)
        else:
            print("Result found in file {} \nBut there were no faces in that file\n\n".format(img_name.filename))
    return

 
research(images, "Christopher")
research(images, "Mark")
research(images, "pizza")
